      "title": "Are humans really the ultimate super-predator?",
      "description": "Humans are often described as the planet's ultimate \"super-predator,\" but wild animals do not fear every human the same way. After analyzing three decades of research, scientists found that animals become much more alert and spend less time feeding when people pose a real threat, such as hunters or fishers. In contrast, tourists, researchers, and other non-lethal humans trigger far weaker and less predictable reactions.",
